[[File:Shinto shrine Kumanohakusangongen 2010-4-4.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Okumiya (April 2010)]]

'''Nōgō Hakusan Shrine''' (のうごうはくさんじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Neo Nōgō, Motosu City, Gifu Prefecture. Its {{ill|lt=Okumiya|Q11445659|WD=Q11445659|1=Okumiya}} is situated at the summit of {{ill|lt=Mount Nōgō Hakusan|Q6922468|WD=Q6922468|1=Mount Nōgōhaku}} (elevation 1,617.3 m). Originally, the Okumiya served as the main sanctuary, but the present main shrine was later constructed for the convenience of local residents.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Kikuri-hime no Kami|Q11619891|WD=Q11619891|1=Kikurihime}} (Hakusan-hime no Kami / {{ill|lt=Hakusan Gongen|Q11579578|WD=Q11579578|1=Hakusan Gongen}})
* {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|WD=Q813858|lt=Izanagi no Mikoto|1=Izanagi}}
* {{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|WD=Q682306|lt=Izanami no Mikoto|1=Izanami}}

=== History ===
According to tradition, the shrine was founded in {{ill|lt=Yōrō|Q1373061|WD=Q1373061|1=Yōrō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=718|Q23534|WD=Q23534|1=718}}) when {{ill|lt=Taichō|Q2388439|WD=Q2388439|1=Taichō}} transferred the deity from {{ill|lt=Hakusan Hime Shrine|Q704702|WD=Q704702|1=Shirayama Hime Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kaga Province|Q907469|WD=Q907469|1=Kaga Province}}. It is said to be one of the “Seven Hakusan Shrines of Hokuriku” (another of these shrines is {{ill|lt=Ōyama Hakusan Shrine|Q11434667|WD=Q11434667|1=Ōyama Hakusan Shrine}}). At the time of its founding, it was called “Hakusan Myōri Gongen,” and it is said that {{ill|lt=Kokūzō Bosatsu|Q416174|WD=Q416174|1=Ākāśagarbha}}, {{ill|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon|Q11404731|WD=Q11404731|lt=Jūichimen Kanzeon Bosatsu|1=Ekādaśamukha}}, and {{ill|lt=Shō Kannon|Q124684411|WD=Q124684411|lt=Shō Kanzeon Bosatsu|1=Āryāvalokiteśvara}} were enshrined.

In June of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. In Meiji 30 ({{ill|lt=1897|Q7847|WD=Q7847|1=1897}}), the present shrine buildings were rebuilt, and in {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 19 ({{ill|lt=2007|Q2024|WD=Q2024|1=2007}}), the main sanctuary underwent restoration.

=== Festivals and rites ===
At the annual festival held on April 13, {{ill|lt=Nōgō no Noh and Kyōgen|Q11612074|WD=Q11612074|1=Nōgō no Noh and Kyōgen}} are performed.

=== Shrine buildings ===
The current main hall dates from the reconstruction of Meiji 30.

=== Cultural properties ===
; Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property (national designation)
* Nōgō no Noh and Kyōgen<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/mumin/motosusi/nougou.html |title=Nōgō no Noh and Kyōgen |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>

; Gifu Prefecture–designated cultural properties
* Japanese bronze mirror (Important Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/kougeihin/motosu/wakyou.html |title=Japanese Bronze Mirror |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Noh masks (Important Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/kougeihin/motosu/noumenn.html |title=Noh Masks |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Noh and Kyōgen costumes (Important Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/kougeihin/motosu/noukyougennshou.html |title=Noh and Kyōgen Costumes |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Bronze temple bell (Important Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/kougeihin/motosu/bonnshou.html |title=Bronze Bell |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Noh and Kyōgen manuscripts (Important Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/tenseki/motosusi/noukyou.html |title=Noh and Kyōgen Manuscripts |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Offering vessels (Important Tangible Folk Cultural Property)<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/yuumin/motosusi/kumotuki.html |title=Offering Vessels |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>

; Motosu City–designated cultural properties
* Buddhist statues<ref>{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.city.motosu.lg.jp/life/kyouiku/culture_asset/kaiga/ |title=Paintings and Sculptures |publisher=Motosu City |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Lotus Sutra written in gold on indigo paper<ref name="tenseki">{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.city.motosu.lg.jp/life/kyouiku/culture_asset/tenseki/ |title=Manuscripts |publisher=Motosu City |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Golden Light Sutra written in gold on indigo paper<ref name="tenseki"/>
* Waniguchi gong<ref name="kogeihin">{{Cite web|Japanese|date= |url=http://www.city.motosu.lg.jp/life/kyouiku/culture_asset/kougei/ |title=Craftworks |publisher=Motosu City |accessdate=2013-04-24}}</ref>
* Noh flute<ref name="kogeihin"/>

=== Access ===
; Main shrine
* The nearest public transportation is about 10 km from {{ill|lt=Tarumi Station|Q7686918|WD=Q7686918|1=Tarumi Station (Gifu)}} on the {{ill|lt=Tarumi Railway Tarumi Line|Q7686917|WD=Q7686917|1=Tarumi Line}} of {{ill|lt=Tarumi Railway|Q11543718|WD=Q11543718|1=Tarumi Railway}}.
* Take the Motosu City Bus Nōgō Line and get off at the “Nōgō” bus stop; about a 5-minute walk.

=== Other ===
There is a theory that this shrine corresponds to “Hananaga Shrine” listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} under {{ill|lt=Ōno District, Mino Province|Q11439757|WD=Q11439757|1=Ōno district}}. Although Nōgō Hakusan Shrine is located in Motosu City (formerly {{ill|lt=Neo Village|Q11536289|WD=Q11536289|1=Neo}} of {{ill|lt=Motosu District|Q1204331|WD=Q1204331|1=Motosu District, Gifu}}), until {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 29 ({{ill|lt=1896|Q7846|WD=Q7846|1=1896}}) it belonged to {{ill|lt=Nishi-Neo Village|Q11628785|WD=Q11628785|1=Nishineo}} of Ōno District.

